  "doi": "10.1016/j.jmb.2011.10.006",
  "title": "Disparate degrees of hypervariable loop flexibility control T-cell receptor cross-reactivity, specificity, and binding mechanism.",
  "journal": "Journal of molecular biology",
  "year": 2011,
  "authors": "Scott DR, Borbulevych OY, Piepenbrink KH, Corcelli SA, Baker BM."
 },
 "executive_summary": "The A6 \u03b1\u03b2 TCR was studied using crystallography, spectroscopy, and computation to understand how flexibility of complementarity-determining region (CDR) loops controls recognition of multiple antigenic peptides presented by MHC-I. The key finding is that CDR3\u03b2 and CDR3\u03b1 hypervariable loops have markedly different energy landscapes: CDR3\u03b2 displays a broad, smooth landscape enabling rapid sampling of multiple conformations compatible with diverse ligands, while CDR3\u03b1 has a rugged landscape constraining sampling to fewer conformations, thereby promoting specificity for particular peptides and MHC proteins. This differential loop flexibility directly explains TCR cross-reactivity and specificity at the molecular level, revealing that TCR binding employs a hybrid mechanism incorporating both conformational selection and induced fit. The work establishes loop dynamics as a fundamental determinant of TCR recognition breadth versus narrowness, with implications for understanding how a limited TCR repertoire achieves both functional cross-reactivity and the selectivity required to distinguish self from non-self.",
